  "footnotes": [
    "Principality of Galicia-Volhynia: Under Daniel of Galicia (r.1238–1264), the principality was the strongest Ukrainian state after Kyiv fell to the Mongols; Daniel briefly accepted a papal crown (1253) to seek Western alliance against the Mongols.",
    "Pereiaslav Agreement (1654): Bohdan Khmelnytsky's Cossack state accepted Muscovite suzerainty to counter Polish-Lithuanian pressure; its exact nature (personal union, protectorate, or incorporation) remains contested by Ukrainian and Russian historians.",
    "Holodomor (1932–1933): Soviet-engineered famine in Ukraine, Kazakhstan, and other regions; killed an estimated 3.5–7.5 million Ukrainians; classified as genocide by Ukraine and many countries.",
    "Crimean Transfer (1954): Khrushchev transferred Crimea from the Russian SFSR to the Ukrainian SSR, largely an administrative act within the unitary Soviet state; became internationally significant after 1991.",
    "Crimean Tatars Deportation (1944): Stalin ordered the deportation of the entire Crimean Tatar population (c.200,000) to Central Asia for alleged collaboration; approximately 18–46% died in transit or exile.",
    "Russian annexation of Crimea (2014): Following the Euromaidan revolution, Russia annexed Crimea after a disputed referendum; unrecognised by the UN General Assembly and most states.",
    "2022 invasion: Russia launched a full-scale invasion on 24 February 2022; Russia subsequently claimed annexation of Zaporizhia, Kherson, Donetsk, and Luhansk oblasts (unrecognised); conflict ongoing."
  ]
